{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603517"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:39:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:39:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15765"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15765"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.32,0.07,0.18,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71144"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8456"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15765"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56615"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7061"},{"type":"tags","id":"8683"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20338"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20341"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71144"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, the testes undergo a complex process of descent from their site of origin to their final location.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements correctly describes testicular development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Testes develop at vertebral level L3","Gubernaculum develops into the round ligament","Testicular descent occurs at 7 weeks gestation","Processus vaginalis closes before birth","Inferior testicular pole attaches to the inguinal ligament"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etestes develop at vertebral level L3\u003C/strong\u003E on the posterior abdominal wall. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egubernaculum\u003C/strong\u003E is a fibrous cord that attaches the inferior pole of the testis to the developing scrotum and later becomes the scrotal ligament, not the \u003Cstrong\u003Eround ligament\u003C/strong\u003E (which is a female structure). \u003Cstrong\u003ETesticular descent\u003C/strong\u003E through the inguinal canal occurs between weeks 28-32 of gestation, not at 7 weeks. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eprocessus vaginalis\u003C/strong\u003E typically remains patent until after birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gubernaculum guides testicular descent and prevents the testes from ascending during growth. It eventually becomes the scrotal ligament in males. Failure of normal testicular descent results in cryptorchidism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Testes develop on the posterior abdominal wall at the level of L3","The gubernaculum arises from the inferior pole of the testis and inserts in the scrotum","Testicular descent through the inguinal canal occurs between weeks 28-32 of gestation","The gubernaculum becomes the scrotal ligament in males, while the round ligament develops in females"],"references":["Titi-Lartey OA, Khan YS. Embryology, Testicle. [Updated 2023 Apr 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557763/","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press.","Gurung P, Yetiskul E, Jialal I. Physiology, Male Reproductive System. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538429/","Foster RA. Male Genital System. Jubb, Kennedy \u0026 Palmer\u0027s Pathology of Domestic Animals: Volume 3. 2016:465\u2013510.e1. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-7020-5319-1.00016-5. Epub 2016 Mar 18. PMCID: PMC7271154.","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56615"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15765"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56615"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T13:24:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T08:26:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8456"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71144"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"